<DOC><DOCNO> AP880801-0045 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0520EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SovietJews     08-01 0151</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet Jews,0153</SECOND><HEAD>Emigration At Eight-Year High</HEAD><DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached anew eight-year-high in July with a total of 1,639 allowed to leavethe country, the agency involved in their resettlement said today.   The total represented the seventh straight monthly rise in thenumber of arrivals at the Vienna, Austria, transit center, theGeneva-based Intergovermental Committee for Migration said. Only930 people opted for new homes in Israel, well below the recentaverage, the committee said.   Last month's figure compared with 1,767 who left the SovietUnion in June 1980, and brought to 7,656 the number of Jewsemigrating in the first seven months of the year, the committeesaid.   The largest official exodus _ 51,330 _ was recorded in 1979before the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled East-Westrelations.   Nearly 270,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlementprogram began in 1971.</TEXT></DOC>